<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-654-359  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 654 359.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Nov 8 1990 v16 n23 p67(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Workers the real threat to security: ETP. (Electronic TrendPublications)andM;</TITLE><SUMMARY>A survey conducted by Electronic Trend Publications (ETP)indicates that employees pose the real threat when it comes tocomputer crimes.andP;  ETP's report indicates that for every hackerthere is one disgruntled employee and eight careless ones that caninflict more severe damage.andP;  The trend of companies to move tomicrocomputer-based networks and away from centralized mainframesystems is offering more opportunity for intrusion and damage.andO;The ETP report shows that commercial users, not including banksand telecommunications, experience the highest frequency ofcomputer crime.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Electronic Trend Publications (Surveys).andO;Topic:     SurveyTrendsComputer CrimesEmployee RelationsComputer Hackers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Types of computer crimes. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Workers the real threat to security: ETPandM;SARATOGA, Calif.andP;  -- Despite media hoopla, hacker attacks don't hold a candleto employee-caused computer damage, says a report from Electronic TrendPublications (ETP).andM;For every sneaky hacker, there is one disgruntled worker and eight carelessones who are wrecking havoc from the inside.andP;  To make matters worse, theproliferation of networked personal computers, rather than centralizedmainframes, offer ever greater opportunities for high-tech intrusion.andM;The causes, impacts and defences against computer crime are the subjects ofCorporate Computer Security Issues and Strategies, a 13-chapter report whichreviews network security, government security requirements, planning, designand implementation issues and system and data security options.andM;The report also details trends in data security, acceptance of voice, retinascan and other bio-security devices; profiles of people who are likely tocommit computer crimes; and, types of system attacks.andM;According to ETP, commercial users, other than banks and telecommunicationsfirms, have experienced the largest percentage of computer assaults.andP;  Nearly40 per cent of computer crime between 1986 and 1988 was related to thissector.andP;  Telecommunication firms and government offices reported the secondworst records.andM;Once inside a system, theft of money was the most common offence committedbetween 1986 and 1988.andP;  But this type of crime -- as well as informationtheft, software damage and software alteration -- decreased substantiallyover the period, note references in the report.andM;Conversely, theft of services shot up from 10 per cent to 34 per cent ofbusinesses surveyed over the same period.andM;Computer system owners are fighting back with a variety of strategies.andP;  Themost common is the age-old password, according to report references.andP;  In thefuture, computer defenders will increasingly use data encryption devices,anti-virus programs and database management systems and other technology.andM;Corporate Computer Security Issues and Strategies is available for $985(U.S.).andO;</TEXT></DOC>